  "voiceover": "Here's the one detail that's hardest to explain away. All four Gospels say the first witnesses to the empty tomb were women. But in first-century Jewish and Roman culture, a woman's testimony was so devalued it often wasn't even accepted in a court of law. So if you were fabricating a story to convince that society, you'd never hand the most important moment to witnesses no one would believe — you'd put respected men there instead. But the Gospel writers kept the embarrassing detail anyway. Why? Because they weren't crafting effective propaganda — they were reporting what actually happened. Historians even have a name for this: the criterion of embarrassment. Awkward, unhelpful details like this aren't how you invent a legend. They're the fingerprint of history.",
